    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but it still feels a bit weird. i saw someone call it \"spooky action at a distance\" once. why did they call it spooky? is there something inherently \"unexplained\" or weird about the way the connection actually works?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein famously called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because the apparent instantaneous collapse of the shared quantum state across vast distances seemed to violate the principle that information cannot travel faster than the speed of light. The \"spookiness\" lies in the non-local nature of this correlation; the particles behave as a single system even when physically separated. However, importantly, this spooky action cannot be used to transmit actual information instantaneously, preserving the laws of relativity.",
      "source": "target",
