    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i get the relativity part. but it just feels like there's something hidden there that we just can't see. like something's pulling the strings or there's some kind of invisible mechanism making it happen behind the scenes. does it actually feel like there's a \"ghost in the machine\" or something when physicists talk about it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While the concept of hidden variables—underlying, unseen instructions dictating the outcomes—was a major historical debate, experiments like Bell tests have largely ruled out simple, local hidden variables. Therefore, modern quantum mechanics suggests there isn't a simple \"mechanism\" pulling strings; the particles genuinely exist in a probabilistic, interconnected state. Many physicists find the inherent non-local interconnectedness genuinely counter-intuitive, but this strangeness is considered a fundamental feature of reality, not a temporary flaw in our understanding.",
      "source": "target",
